  "text": "Face images in many face recognition applications are compressed and reconstructed by conventional schemes such as JPEG. But there would be some annoying blocking artifacts in a picture when compressed at low bit rates by JPEG, which is presented in Fig. 2 . Such artifacts not only affect image quality, but also affect the performance of feature extraction in subsequent image processing tasks such as face recognition and image classification. Some post-processing methods such as Artifacts Reduction Convolutional Neural Network [CITATION_1] (AR-CNN) are indeed useful for deblocking and artifacts reduction, which is shown in Fig. 3 . However, these deblocking networks usually involve some iterative process that consumes high computational resource. Moreover, the optimization goal of the deblocking network is not entirely consistent with that of the face recognition network, that is to say, training a network that enhances image quality alone does not necessarily mean achieving the optimal result of face recognition tasks.",
